The '''white-throated treerunner''' ('''''Pygarrhichas albogularis''''') is a [[species]] of bird in the family [[Furnariidae]]. It is the only species in the [[genus]] '''''Pygarrhichas'''''. The white-throated treerunner is about {{Convert|15|cm|in|abbr=on}} long, with a stiff and rounded tail. The {{birdgloss|upperparts}} are dark brown, turning red on the lower back and tail and contrasting sharply with the throat and chest of a bright white. The rest of the {{birdgloss|underparts}} are coarsely mottled with white. The bill is long, slightly curved upwards. The general appearance is reminiscent of a [[nuthatch]] (''Sitta spp.''), although they are not directly related. Like the Sittidae, Furnariidae tirelessly scours the trunks and branches of old trees for the small [[arthropods]] that make up its food, spiraling up the trunks, or sometimes moving head down. The white-throated treerunner consumes small [[invertebrates]] found on bark and nests in tree cavities. Outside of the breeding season, it may form [[mixed-species foraging flock]]s with other bird species.

The White-throated treerunner inhabits the southern tip of the American continent, in [[Chile]] and [[Argentina]], from [[Santiago]] and [[Mendoza, Argentina|Mendoza]] to [[Tierra del Fuego]]. It seeks out forests with large trees – the old trunks offer suitable nesting sites – whether they are lowland or highland, dense or open. It was described in 1831 by [[Phillip Parker King]], a British explorer of [[Patagonia]] and [[Tierra del Fuego]]. Its systematic placement has remained unclear within its family, superficial similarities with other Furnariidae gleaning their food from the bark of trees seem to be the result of an [[Convergent evolution|evolutionary convergence]]. [[Molecular phylogenetics|Molecular phylogenies]] seem to link it to the genera ''[[Microxenops]]'' and ''[[Ochetorhynchus]]''. No subspecies is described. Its range is relatively large and there is no evidence of decline in numbers, so the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] considers this bird to be of "[[least concern]]".

== Taxonomy ==
[[File:White-throated Treerunner - Gould.jpg|left|thumb|180px|alt=A drawing of a black and orange-red bird at the branch of tree|Plate of [[John Gould]], who describes the species under the name of ''Dendrodramus leucosternus'' in 1839.]]
The white-throated treerunner was scientifically described in 1831 under the [[protonym]] ''Dendrocolaptes albogularis'' by the British explorer [[Phillip Parker King]], who visited [[Patagonia]] and [[Tierra del Fuego]] among other places. The [[Specific name (zoology)|specific name]], ''albogularis'', means "white-throated" in [[Latin]]; the type locality is not known but is supposed to be the [[Strait of Magellan]]. In 1837, the Argentine zoologist [[Hermann Burmeister]] removed the species from the genus ''[[Dendrocolaptes]]'', which today includes only five species of climbers, and assigned it a separate genus, ''Pygarrhichas'', giving it the novel specific name of "''ruficaudis''" (from Latin meaning "red-tailed").<ref name="James Peters">{{Cite book |last=Peters|first=James Lee |title=Check-list of birds of the world|url=https://archive.org/details/checklistofbirds71951pete?view=theater#page/146/mode/2up|volume=7|year=1951|page=147-148|publisher=Cambridge, Harvard University Press }}</ref> Burmeister constructs this name from the [[ancient Greek]] πυγη (''pugē'') meaning "rump" and αρριχος (''arrhikhos'') denoting wicker, to refer to the stiffness of the bird's tail helping it progress along trunks.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Jobling |first=James A. |title= Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird Names|publisher= [[Bloomsbury Publishing]]|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-RfSBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA325|date=June 2010|page=325|isbn=978-1-4081-3326-2 }}</ref>

In 1839, English ornithologist [[John Gould]], presumably unaware of King's work,<ref name="Richard Crawshay">{{Cite book |last=Crawshay |first=Richard |title= The birds of Tierra del Fuego|publication-place=London|url=https://archive.org/details/birdsoftierradel00craw/page/80/mode/2up?view=theater|year=1907|page=80-81 |publisher= B. Quaritch}}</ref> independently described the species in ''[[Zoology of the Voyage of H.M.S. Beagle]]'' as ''Dendrodramus leucosternus'' (from the ancient Greek for "white-bellied"). He observed the species on the [[Chiloé Island]], and found similarities with the [[Eurasian treecreeper]] (''Certhia familiaris'') in its behavior.<ref name="John Gould">{{Cite book |last=Gould |first=John|title=The zoology of the voyage of H.M.S. Beagle, under the command of Captain Fitzroy, R.N., during the years 1832 to 1836|url=https://archive.org/details/zoologyofvoyageo03darw/page/82/mode/2up?view=theater|volume=3:''Birds''|year=1839|page= 82-83}}</ref> In 1890, English zoologist [[Philip Lutley Sclater]] placed this genus in the now obsolete family ''Dendrocolaptidae'',<ref name="Philip Sclater">{{Cite book |last= Sclater |first= Philip Lutley|title=Catalog of Birds in the British Museum|url=https://archive.org/details/catalogueofbirds15brit/page/126/mode/2up?view=theater|volume=15:''Tracheophonae''|year=1890 |page=126-127}}</ref> a position changed by paleornithologist [[Alan Feduccia]] in 1973 who placed the genus in its current family, [[Furnariidae]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last= Feduccia |first= Alan |title=Evolutionary Trends in the Neotropical Ovenbirds and Woodhewers|journal= Ornithological Monographs|url=https://archive.org/details/catalogueofbirds15brit/page/126/mode/2up?view=theater|volume=13|year=1973|issue= 13 |pages= i–69 |doi=10.2307/40166692 |jstor= 40166692 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last= Clench |first= Mary Heimerdinger |title=Body Pterylosis of Woodcreepers and Ovenbirds (Dendrocolaptidae and Furnariidae) |journal=[[Ornithology (journal)|The Auk]]|volume=112|issue=3|year=1995|page= 800-804}}</ref> According to the [[International Ornithological Congress]] and Alan P. Peterson, no subspecies is distinguished.<ref>{{cite web | title= Pygarrhichas albogularis (PP King, 1831)  |url=https://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/ovenbirds/| website=IOC World Bird List – Version 11.2 | access-date=16 January 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title= Pygarrhichas albogularis in Furnariidae | website=Zoonomen Nomenclature Resource Page | date=1 Mar 2002 | url=http://www.zoonomen.net/avtax/pa05.html| access-date=16 January 2022}}</ref>

===Placement in the family===
In 1839, Gould mentions that English zoologist [[George Robert Gray]] would relate the white-throated treerunner to the genus ''Dendroplex'' described by English ornithologist [[William Swainson]].<ref name="John Gould"/> In the 2003 ''[[Handbook of the Birds of the World]]'', Volume 8, American ornithologist [[James Van Remsen Jr.]] explains that while P''. albogularis'' is traditionally related to the ''Xenops sittines'' and other tree-bark gleaning Furnariidae, plumage and biogeography suggest that these different species are not directly related and that their similarities are merely the result of [[convergent evolution]]. It has also been suggested that similarities in plumage and foraging behavior may bring the white-throated treerunner closer to [[Synallaxis]] of the genus ''[[Aphrastura]]''.<ref name="HBW"/>

Two [[Molecular phylogenetics|molecular phylogenies]] of the family published in 2009, and then one in 2011, negate such relatedness and clarify the evolutionary history somewhat while implying significant classification changes. The naming of a subfamily (that of "Pygarrhichinae") or tribe (that of "Pygarrhichini", within the subfamily Furnariinae) is advanced for a [[clade]] that would include the white-throated treerunner, the [[rufous-tailed xenops]] (''Microxenops milleri''), species of the genus ''[[Ochetorhynchus]]'', and would absorb the [[band-tailed Eremobius]] (O''. phoenicurus'') as well as the [[crag chilia]] (''O. melanurus''), previously placed in the [[Monotypic taxon|monotypic genera]] ''Eremobius'' and ''Chilia'' respectively.<ref name="Furnariidae">{{cite web | last=Boyd|first= John |title=FURNARIIDA II - Grallariidae, Rhinocryptidae, Formicariidae, Furnariidae|url=http://jboyd.net/Taxo/List14.html|website=TiF Checklist |date=March 14, 2016|access-date=16 January 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1=Irestedt | first1=Martin | last2=Fjeldså | first2=Jon | last3=Dalén | first3=Love |last4=Ericson|first4= Per GP | title=Convergent evolution, habitat shifts and variable diversification rates in the ovenbird-woodcreeper family (Furnariidae) |journal=[[BMC Evolutionary Biology]]| year=2009|volume=9|issue=1| page=268|issn= 1471-2148|doi=10.1186/1471-2148-9-268| pmid=19930590 | pmc=2787525 | doi-access=free | bibcode=2009BMCEE...9..268I }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1=Moyle | first1=Robert G. | last2=Chesser | first2=Terry | last3=Brumfield | first3= Robb T.|last4= Tello|first4= Jose G. |last5= Marchese |first5=Daniel J. |last6=Cracraft |first6=Joel |title=Phylogeny and phylogenetic classification of the antbirds, ovenbirds, woodcreepers, and allies (Aves: Passeriformes: infraorder Furnariides) |url=https://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/index2.php?url=http%3A%2F%2Fargentavis.org%2F2012%2Freferencias%2Fdocumento_86.pdf%2Findex.html#federation=archive.wikiwix.com|journal=[[Cladistics (journal)|Cladistics]]| year=2009|volume=25|issue=4| pages=386–405 |doi=  10.1111/j.1096-0031.2009.00259.x| pmid=34879609 | s2cid=35771385 |doi-access=free }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1=Derryberry | first1=Elizabeth P. | last2=Claramunt | first2=Santiago | last3=Derryberry | first3=Graham |last4= Chesser |first4= R. Terry|last5= Cracraft |first5=Joel |last6=Aleixo |first6=Alexandre|first7=Jorge |last7= Pérez-Emán|first8=J.V. Jr.|last8=Remsen  |first9=Robb T.|last9= Brumfield |title=Lineage diversification and morphological evolution in a large -scale continental radiation: the Neotropical ovenbirds and woodcreepers (Aves: Furnariidae) |journal=Evolution|url=https://www.museum.lsu.edu/~Remsen/2011-Evolution.pdf| year=2011|volume=65|issue=10| pages=2973–2986 |doi= 10.1111/j.1558-5646.2011.01374.x| pmid=21967436 | s2cid=25163221 }}</ref>

