==Description==
[[File:White-throated Treerummer (Pygarrhichas albogularis) (15774411279) (cropped).jpg|right|thumb|180px|alt=Black, orange-red bird with white belly at the branch of tree|Adult white-throated treerunner.]]
The white-throated treerunner is {{Convert|15-16|cm|in|abbr=on}} long on average, with a weight between {{convert|20|–|27|g|oz}}.<ref name="HBW">{{cite web | last=Remsen|first= James van Jr. | website=[[Handbook of the Birds of the World]]|title=White-throated Treerunner (''Pygarrhichas albogularis'') | url=http://www.hbw.com/species/white-throated-treerunner-pygarrhichas-albogularis | publisher= [[Lynx Edicions]]|year=2016|access-date=2019-09-03}}</ref><ref name="RozziJimenez2014">{{cite book | last1=Rozzi | first1=R. | last2=Jimenez | first2=J.E. | title=Magellanic Sub-Antarctic Ornithology: First Decade of Long-Term Bird Studies at the Omora Ethnobotanical Park, Cape Horn Biosphere Reserve, Chile | publisher=University of North Texas Press & Ediciones Universidad de Magallanes | year=2014 | isbn=978-1-57441-531-5 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fyk9BAAAQBAJ&pg=PA62 | access-date=2019-09-03 | page=62}}</ref> It has an appearance reminiscent of the [[nuthatch]], with its overall look and plumage, unlike other species in the Furnariidae.<ref name="HBW"/> [[Wing chord (biology)|Wing chord]] is from {{Convert|76–86|mm|in|abbr=on}}, tail is {{Convert|52–65|mm|in|abbr=on}}, and torso from {{Convert|20–23.7|mm|in|abbr=on}}.<ref name="Rozzi2010">{{cite book | last1=Rozzi | first1=R. | last2=Massardo | first2=F. | last3=Program | first3=S.A.B.C. | title=Multi-ethnic Bird Guide of the Sub-Antarctic Forests of South America | publisher=Sub-Antarctic Biocultural Conservation Program, University of North Texas - Universidad de Magallanes | year=2010 | isbn=978-1-57441-282-6 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8jyBDt4kpDEC&pg=PA63 | access-date=2019-09-03 | page=63}}</ref> The [[iris (anatomy)|iris]] is dark brown.<ref name="HBW"/> It has a long {{birdgloss|beak}}, at around {{Convert|16–23.8|mm|in|abbr=on}} with a slight upward curve.<ref name="RozziJimenez2014"/><ref name="Rozzi2010"/> Its upper mandible is dark gray and lower mandible a whitish-pale gray. The feet are dark gray, blackish or brown.<ref name="HBW"/>

The species is easily recognized by its white throat, contrasting with its upper parts.<ref name="Rozzi2010"/> Its face is blackish-brown and slightly darker than its head {{birdgloss|crown}}, which is a dull brown. The back is a paler chestnut-brown,<ref name="HBW"/> pulling against the red rump and tail.<ref name="Rozzi2010"/><ref name="Chester2010">{{cite book | last=Chester | first=Sharon | title=A Wildlife Guide to Chile: Continental Chile, Chilean Antarctica, Easter Island, Juan FernÃ¡ndez Archipelago | publisher=Princeton University Press | year=2010 | isbn=978-1-4008-3150-0 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qrI5ph6BWiIC&pg=PA250 | access-date=2019-09-03 | page= 250-251}}</ref> The wing [[coverts]] are dark brown, with red or chestnut brown on the feather edges and tail end. The primaries are darker, the remiges black-brown with light edges and inner primaries marked with a short, light red wing bar. The tail is rounded, with rigid [[Flight feather#Rectrices|rectrices]] with shortened [[Feather#Classification|barbs]] ending in small spines up to {{Convert|9|mm|in|abbr=on}} long.<ref name="HBW"/>

A large white zone covers the treerunner's cheek and throat, descending to the middle of the chest. The rest of the lower parts, to the {{birdgloss|undertail coverts}}, are made up of white feathers largely bordered with dark brown, giving an irregularly spotted appearance. Both sexes of adults look similar. The chick is distinguished by an [[ochre]]-striped crown and back, and often with blackish borders on the throat feathers.<ref name="HBW"/>

== Ecology and behavior ==
[[File:Rayadito, Tomé.jpg|right|thumb|180px|alt=Black and white belly thorn-tailed bird at the branch of tree|The white-throated treerunner may feed in flocks with other bird species, such as [[thorn-tailed rayadito]].]]
===Vocalizations===
{{Birdsong|species=''Pygarrhichas albogularis''|url=https://xeno-canto.org/species/Pygarrhichas-albogularis}}
The white-throated treerunner gives off a short and piercing cry, evoking a rapid succession of water droplets.<ref name="Rozzi2010"/> Its [[contact call]] is described as a loud, fast, metallic "kik-ik", "tsi-ik" or "tsik", which is repeated rapidly. The treerunner can also emit a sonorous "peet peet", and during flight, a dry "tic".<ref name="HBW"/>

===Food===
Similar in behavior to nuthatches (''Sitta spp.''), the white-throated treerunner is a restless bird, moving in a jerky manner and changing direction rapidly. The bird may descend from trunks head first. It scours the trunks and large branches of old trees, often spiraling around the trunks,<ref name="Rozzi2010"/> searching for small insects and their larvae in every crevice for food, sometimes tapping lightly with its bill, much like a woodpecker,<ref name="Lester Leroy">{{cite journal | last=Short|first= Lester Leroy Jr.|title=Observations of the Nuthatch-Like White-Throated Treerunner (''Pygarrhichas albogularis'') in Argentina |journal=[[Ornithological Applications|The Condor]]|url=https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/condor/v071n04/p0438-p0439.pdf|volume=71|issue=4|date=1969|pages= 438–439|doi= 10.2307/1365748|jstor= 1365748}}</ref> or digging out larvae from under the bark with its bill.<ref>{{cite journal | last1=Becerra Serial |first1= Rodrigo M.|last2=Grigera |first2=Dora |title=Dinámica estacional del ensamble de aves de un bosque norpatagónico de lenga ( Nothofagus pumilio ) y su relación con la disponibilidad de sustratos de alimentación  |journal=[[El Hornero]]|url=http://www.scielo.org.ar/pdf/hornero/v20n2/v20n2a01.pdf|volume=20|issue=2|date=2005 }}</ref> It may use its tail for support, or it may use its tail as a support for the insects. It may use their tail for support, but it also does a lot of tail-first browsing.<ref name="HBW"/> It explores trunks quickly and spends more time foraging in smaller branches, looking for prey at the base of leaf petioles.<ref name="Lester Leroy"/>

Its diet is little known, consisting of [[arthropods]] including adults and larvae of [[beetles]], as well as [[diptera]].<ref name="HBW"/><ref name="RozziJimenez2014"/> A study conducted in the province of Osorno showed that the white-throated treerunner mainly forages on trees such as [[Nothofagus dombeyi|Coigüe]] (''Nothofagus dombeyi''), but also [[Nothofagus obliqua|Neuquén Roble]] (''N. obliqua''), [[Eucryphia cordifolia|Ulmo]] (''Eucryphia cordifolia''), and more generally on dead trees, even when other tree and shrub species are available. These preferences could be explained by the structure of the bark and the greater abundance of accessible insects.<ref>{{cite journal | last1=Gantz| first1=Alberto | last2=Yañez| first2=Miguel | last3=Orellana| first3=José I. |last4= Sade |first4= Soraya |last5= Valdivia|first5= Carlos E.|title=Use of tree species by White-throated treerunner (Pygarrhichas albogularis King) in a secondary native forest of southern Chile|url=https://www.scielo.br/j/isz/a/8J7m6MK73BF4QYSZB5R6C3n/?format=pdf&lang=en|journal=Iheringia. Série Zoologia| year=2015|volume=105|issue=2| page=193-198|doi=10.1590/1678-476620151052193198| s2cid=87924718 |doi-access=free}}</ref> In some locations, particularly on islands with no terrestrial predators, the species may also feed on the ground.<ref name="Rozzi2010"/> Outside the breeding season, it may form [[mixed-species foraging flock]] with the [[thorn-tailed rayadito]] (''Aphrastura spinicauda)'', as well as with the [[striped woodpecker]] (''Veniliornis lignarius''), and sometimes also with the [[fire-eyed diucon]] (Xolmis pyrope),<ref name="Vuilleumier François">{{cite journal | last=Vuilleumier| first=François |title=Mixed Species Flocks in Patagonian Forests, with Remarks on Interspecies Flock Formation|journal= [[Ornithological Applications|The Condor]]| year=1967|volume=69|issue=4| pages=400–404 |doi=10.2307/1366201| jstor=1366201 }}</ref> [[Patagonian sierra finch]] (''Phrygilus patagonicus'') and the [[black-chinned siskin]] (''Spinus barbatus'').<ref>{{cite journal | last1=Ippi | first1=Silvina |last2=Trejo| first2=Ana |url=https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/on/v014n03/p0353-p0362.pdf|title=Dinámica y estructura de bandadas mixtas de aves en un bosque de Lenga (Nothofagus pumilio) del noroeste de la Patagonia argentina|journal= [[Neotropical Ornithological Society|Ornitología Neotropical]]| year=2003|volume=14| page= 353-362}}</ref>

=== Breeding ===
The white-throated treerunner nests in tree cavities. It may nest in the trunks of senescent or fire-damaged trees,<ref name="RozziJimenez2014"/><ref name="Chester2010"/> but is not as successful at this task as other species such as woodpeckers and therefore also reuses existing cavities. Observations of antagonistic behavior by the woodpecker toward other species reusing tree cavities suggest that it competes with these birds in cavity use more than it provides them with new nesting sites by excavating its own hole.<ref>{{cite journal | last1=Tomasevic | first1=Jorge A.|last2=Estades| first2=Cristián F.|url=https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/on/v017n01/p0001-p0014.pdf|title=Stand attributes and the abundance of secondary cavity-nesting birds in southern beech (Nothofagus) forests in South-Central Chile|journal= [[Neotropical Ornithological Society|Ornitología Neotropical]]| year=2006|volume=17|issue=1| page=1-14 }}</ref> A study of the thorn-tailed rayadito to assess whether or not broadcast conspecific songs attracted individuals to a suitable nesting area showed that, on the contrary, cavity-nesting birds-including white-throated treerunners and [[Northern house wren|house wren]]s-avoided competitive areas. The white-throated treerunner, however, readily uses nest boxes.<ref>{{cite journal | last1=Quilodrán| first1= Claudio S. |last2=Estades| first2=Cristián F.|last3=Vásquez|first3=Rodrigo A.|title=Conspecific effect on habitat selection of a territorial cavity-nesting bird |journal= [[The Wilson Journal of Ornithology]]| year=2014|volume=126|issue=3| pages=534–543|issn=1559-4491|doi= 10.1676/13-108.1| s2cid= 84223349 |hdl=10533/148552|hdl-access=free}}</ref>

The nest cavity is usually between {{Convert|3–8|mm|in|abbr=on}}, above the ground, and is {{Convert|25–40|cm|in|abbr=on}}, deep. There is no lining other than the chips from the excavation, but a carpet of grasses and feathers has been reported once. The breeding season probably spans the southern spring and summer, with eggs laid in November-December and young hatching in December. The white-throated treerunner is thought to be [[Monogamy in animals|monogamous]], laying two to three eggs.<ref name="HBW"/> Eggs preserved at the [[Natural History Museum, London|Natural History Museum]] in London and measured by English naturalist [[Eugene William Oates]] are approximately {{convert|21.5-22|×|16.7-17|mm|in|abbr=on|sigfig=2}}.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Oates | first= Eugene William|url=https://archive.org/details/catalogueofcolle03bri/page/182/mode/2up?view=theater|title= Catalog of the collection of birds' eggs in the British Museum |journal= [[The Wilson Journal of Ornithology]]| year=1903|volume=3| page=182-183}}</ref> Capture-mark-recapture data from 35 individuals in the [[Cape Horn Biosphere Reserve]] indicate a longevity of at least 3 years and 8 months.<ref name="RozziJimenez2014"/>

== Distribution and habitat ==
[[File:BosqLenga1.jpg|right|thumb|180px|alt=A view of the lenga forest|[[Nothofagus pumilio|Lenga forest]] (''Nothofagus pumilio'') is a typical habitat of the white-throated treerunner.]]
This species lives in central and southern [[Chile]] and western [[Argentina]], from [[Santiago]] and [[Mendoza, Argentina|Mendoza]] to [[Tierra del Fuego]].<ref name="HBW"/> It is found in the south of its distribution in the southernmost forest in the world, on [[Hornos Island|Horn Island]].<ref name="Rozzi2010"/> It lives from sea level to 1,200 m of altitude,<ref name="iucn status 12 November 2021"/><ref name="HBW"/> populating forests with large trees, whether dense or not, but avoiding young forests.<ref name="Vuilleumier François"/> The white-throated treerunner seeks out forests dominated by "false beech" species of the genus ''[[Nothofagus]]''.<ref name="HBW"/> It exploits the trunks at mid-height of trees up to the top of the canopy as a small woodpecker would.<ref name="Rozzi2010"/> The species is sedentary, but can be erratic outside the breeding season.<ref name="HBW"/>

== In relationship with humans ==
===In culture===
The white-throated treerunner appears in some traditional [[Yagan|Yagana]] stories as ''tatajurj'', where it accompanies women and collects [[epiphytic fungi]] of the genus ''[[Cyttaria]]'' (katran in Yagan) from the trunks of [[Nothofagus betuloides|Magellanic Beech]] (''N. betuloides''), [[Nothofagus pumilio|Lenga]] (''N. pumilio''), and [[Nothofagus antarctica|Ñire]] (''N. antarctica'') trees.<ref name="Rozzi2010"/>

===Status and threats===
The white-throated treerunner needs to have old [[Plant senescence|senescent trees]] available for nesting, a specific and scarce habitat that deserves a conservation effort.<ref name="Rozzi2010"/> However, it is quite common, and present in many protected areas such as [[Vicente Pérez Rosales National Park]], [[Puyehue National Park]], [[Nahuelbuta National Park]] and [[La Campana National Park]] in Chile, or [[Tierra del Fuego National Park]] in Argentina.<ref name="HBW"/> The range of the white-throated treerunner is estimated at {{Convert|470,000|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} and its numbers are believed to be stable; thus, the species is considered of "[[least concern]]" by the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]].<ref name="iucn status 12 November 2021" />

